    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\n\nNo\n\n### Feature description\n\nHere is an in insanely useful feature - described here:\r\nhttps://github.com/t9md/atom-vim-mode-plus/wiki/AdvancedTopicTutorial#5-modify-operators-behavior-by-o-to-make-it-operate-on-occurrence\r\n\r\nI don't think I can give a description of it justice, but it's extremely handy to be able to mark \"occurrences\" of a thing (by doing a visual select and type \"g\" \"o\"), then perform an action, such as \"c\" \"i\" \"p\", which would normally change inner paragraph, but having a pre-marked \"occurrences\" will automatically put you in multi-cursor mode on all of the selected occurrences within the target.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, instead of pre-marking the occurrences, performing an action like \"c\" \"o\" \"i\" \"p\" would automatically use the token which the cursor is currently located on as the target.\r\n\r\nExample\r\n\r\nThis is the text.\r\nI like the text here.\r\nHere is more text, and this is also the text.\r\n\r\nIf your cursor were on any of the \"text\" occurrences, and you typed coipbanana<esc>, then all occurrences of \"text\" will now be changed with \"banana\":\r\n\r\nThis is the banana.\r\nI like the banana here.\r\nHere is more banana, and this is also the banana.\r\n\r\nThis really simplifies multiple cursors when you already know what your target and \"occurrence\" (or token or whatever you want to call it) are.",
    "closed_at": null,
